{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_frenchbulldog_ver04/data/sn83045433/00280764152/1921030701/0225.xml":{"full_text":"lFS==n ?ie Jia!3litaal0ii kkke 1\nu I I _ I?!? mm I\nSECTION TWO?PAGE 7. WASHINGTON. D. C., MONDAY, MARCH 7, 1921. PAGE 7?SECTION TWO.\nBARCLAY BANKING 1\nHEAD DISCUSSES\nI TRADE SITUATION\nConcerning Industry Outlook,\nSays Cross-roads\nyg, Are Reached.\nWisdom necessary\nShould Quickly Recover From\nStagnation If Broad Views I,\nAre Exercised.\nOa occasion of the annual I\nstockholder meeting of Barclays\nBank. oae of the leading instltutlona\nof- Great Britain. Frederick\nC Goodenough. chairman of the\nkaak. made extended comments\nupon the world's business situation I\naad la particular oa tha situation 1\nas It affects Great Britain. Tha fol- I\nlowing extracts from his address\nhare soma beartntr on our own ra- J\nlatlon to the International sltuatiOA.\n\"I fael strongly that ws are now\nat the cross-roads so far as the\noutlook for industry Is concerned,\nand that upon our choice of meth- I\nods depends whether we return to\nprosperity via a protracted or via\na short period of distress and unemployment.\nThe world Is passing through a\nMgperlod of resettlement, and If we\nITake a broad view of the situation,\nespecially as regards assMtsnce to\n^distressed countries and the various i\ncomplexities surrounding indemnity 1\npayments and allied Indebtedness. 1\nsee no reason why we should not\nquickly recover from the present\nstagnation. But if our outlook Is\nto be narrow, not only will trade\nravlval be delayed, but our fu?'?\nwill be prejudiced. We cannot af-1\nford to Ignore the Interdependence\nof nations?a more important factor\nnow than during the period which\nfollowed the Napoleonic wars?and\nour aim should be the creation of\nwhat would really be a Financial\nLeague of Nations, composed of all I\nthe countries able to help. The matter\nIs urgent, and the world cannot I\nafford delay; our part Is to show\nno hesitation In our readiness to\ntaks up our share of the burden.\nOrt at lUal of TraaWe.\nUnless we can get to the root of\nthe causes which at the present\ntime are shutting down, partially\nor wholly, the markets which In I\nprewar times took from us many I\nmillions of our output, and again\nrestore thrjn to normal conditions,\nit would seem that a recovery in\nih< Industrial position must be\nB^very slow indeed. Until the dis- I\ntressed countrlss of Europe are I\nd^artfd upon a fresh financial baaisl\nwhich is fundamentally sound,\ntheir markets will continue to re-1\nmain wholly or partially closed.\nWith their unsound currencies they\ncan neither pay nor obtain credit. I\nand the credit schemes which have\nbeen propoaed are merely palliatives I\nto the present situation. They will I\nact only very slowly, and. so far as\nwe can see. they will not provide a\nremedy as quickly as the disease of I\nunsound currency will drive those\ncountries Into bankruptcy. I,\nPrivate Remedies Wfflealt. I,\n\"it baa been thought by some that\nany remedial meaaures had better |i\nbe left to private enterprise, but\nthat la open to this difficulty, that I\nin many Instances the risks In-11\nvolvcd are neither banking, nor la-1\nsurance. nor trading risks, but they\nars political risks over which pri- i\nvate enterprise can exercise no sort I\nof control. For this reason credit\ncannot be forthcoming from private i\nsources to an extent which will be I\nadequate to what is required, and, I!\nalthough a great volume of credit!\nhas already been granted to Europe\nLxmco the armistice, so little progress\npkhas been achieved that It would I.\nseem that organised International\n%ction Is needed before any satis-1\nfactory results can be secured.\n\"At the root of the troubles of tne\ndistressed coantrles la the Inability 1\nto meet expenditure out of revenue\nand the consequent necessity of\nmaking up the deficiency by the\nhelp of an unsound system of currency\nwhich enables paper, without\na specific backing or ratio of vslue.\nto be created for the purpoae of #11Imm\nup tho gap: If this process is to\nb? arrested before bankruptcy supervenes\nInternational assistance Is\nrequired?at all events for the\nsmaller eoutrlea?to enable them to\ntide over the Interval of time until\nthey can reorganise thslr Internal I\nposition by the adjustment of rave- I\nnue and expenditure and by trade.\nMast There be Cieaeral Bankruptcy?\nThara aaems to be no other way\nshort of a general reconstruction\nafter bankruptcy; thla would Involve\nenormous loss of capital, followed\nby long, painful and dangerous\nprocess of recovery, all ot\nwhich would add to the dlfflcultlea I\nof trade and Increase the present\nunemployment.\n-If international securities w?re\ncreated to #11 this gap some form\nof International control would be\nA necessary In order that sound fl- I\nnanclal and economic princlplea\n?night bo insisted upon. The carrying\nout of such a scheme would\nprobably Involve some Inflation of\ncredit In this and other countriea.\nSuch Inflation should, however, resalt\nin the re-opening of trade and\nA NEW ENDORSEMENT.\n\nTV Beasts OoMlttee ee Keeeaatreciioa\nutoi?T<h new laglslatETthst\na forties ef the <ep.lt. Is\ntbe teoisga dopermeets of aatleaal\nI_aka aay he laTMted Is leag term\naererttlea sad eomijn \"la order to\ndee greater oeearity to the avtsgs\nUl to aasist la prevMiag heatee fee\nthe thrifty.\"\nOar nrot Mortgage Xetre. aa tmeroToS\nWsohisgtoe real oats*. e?S\navails Me la toeeU sad Urge dessalsattoas.\nm swartzelL, RHEEM k\nHENSEYCO.\nr 727 Fiftacatk Stmt N. W.\nL Wnlh|*M, P. C.\nI Tki Nahou't Horn* Tom i\nCOLD STORAGE F\nBELOW THOS\n____\nStocks of Mutton Un\nBeef, Poultry, and\nBiff C\n(Tie WukliffM Hi\nNo country In the world hu developed\naa elaborate a system ^t>f\ncold storage warehouses as those\nla the United States. As k matter\nof fact refrigeration of this character\nwas almost unknown la Europe\na few years ago. The cold storage\nwarehouses built In France by\nthe American army hare added very\nmaterially to the storage capacity\nof that country.\nCOLD 8TOBAGB HOLDINGS Or\nFeb. 1, Feb. 1.\n1921. 1930.\nPosada. Pouds\nBetter 44.Ml.3aO 86,876.1\nCbeeee 40.46t.4J7 84.416.8\nCase tfp 1 .?62.860 15.866.1\nFuses HI* J4.766.786 16.393.fl\nPeel try 66.888.851 82.246.1\na ad muttoa 78.067.564 7.786.0\nBeef prod acta.... 14J.877.264 286.752.1\nPark product*.. 784.806.185 874.412^\nMlae. meats 84.686.187 118.228.4\n~T?tal 1.J8J.614.486 1.862.514.4\nThis table shows that the total\nholdings of these commodities on\nFebruary 1. 19^1, amounted to 1.228,666.006\npounds compared with a\nlittle over 1.500.000.000 pounds on\nFebruary 1. 1920. This is a decrease\nin the total of about It per cent.\nDuring the month of Januayy total\nholdings increaaed a iittl* over 10\nper cent, due largely to the increase\nin pork, mutton and beef, which\nnormally show an excess movement\ninto storage at this season of the\nyear.\nThe most striking change shown\nin this table is that for lamb and\nmutton which on the first of February\nthis year showed total noldings\nof 78,000.000 pounds, compared with\nonly 8,000,000 pounds on the same\ndate last year. This is an Increase\nof over 000 per cent for the year.\nPrevious to October 1, 1920, 13.000.000\npounds was the largest amount\nof this commodity ever held at one\ntime in the United States. The big\nincrease in lamb and mutton is\nlargely accounted for by the heavy\nimports during the recent months\nThe total imports of mutton and\nlamb for ths calendar year 1920\namounted to 101.168,319 pounds compared\nwith t.209.1t2 ''pounds in 1919\nand only <08.000 pounds in 1918.\nImports for the month of December\nalone were more than 10,000,000\npounds, or considerably in excess\nof the total imports for the whole\nof the year 1919. In October. 1920,\nImports amounted to more than 27,000,000\npounds. Of the total amount\nof lamb and mutton in storage 69,000,000\npounds, or 80 per cent is held\nIs. therefore, preferable t<> inflation\nIncurred as a result of trade stagnation\nand unemployment doles.\nIstersaHsssl GsTeraaeit Debt*.\n\"There is also the question of our\nown foreign debt and the debts that\nare owing to us by other foreign\nnations, and here the difficulty\narises that, whereas the money we\nowe abroad?and It is a very large\nsum?is for the most part payable\non demand, that which^ is owing to\nmm depends for payment upon the\nreturn of those who are our debtors\nto a -sound financial position, and\nthis will take time. It may be that\nas a matter ftf business only It\nvould pay us to make concessions\nIn respect of debts owing to us by\nsilled governments, provided we do\nnot thereby prejudice, our own ability\nto pay. We might, for instance,\nconsider the possibility of a part\ncancellation of those sums lent to\nour allies for the purpose of pur- j\nchasing munitions in tMs country.\nwhile retaining their liability for;\nthose sums which In effect repre-\nent money lent to them by the\nUnited States through ourselves.\nSuch a policy must, of course, depend\nupon any new atrreement that\nmay be made with regard to our\ndebts to our allies, but If an ordinary\nbusiness man finds It to his\nadvantage to forgive some portion of\nwhat is due to him. in order that\nhis debtor may be put on his business\nlegs again, we. as a nation,\nmight find it wise to do the same\nwith regard to the debts of our allies.\nThe better exchange conditions\nwhich should follow might\nenable a gre^t deal of What Is already\nowing to us on trade transactions\nto be paid, and this would\n\nThe Vatioaal City Tl\nBank J\n(teal)\nef Mew Tart\nCond\nCAPITAL*\nSURPLUS CASH on\nand /\"\"J\nUNDIVIDED\nPROFITS\n$106^975.99 United St.\nStock to I\nBanking i\nOther Am\n\nCapital, Si\nDcpotits\nDa* to Si\nuSESd\nDa* to Pa\nOthtf^Biu\nAccept 8jic\nBart (Mm ???22\nIOLDINGS\n>E OF YEAR AGO\nusually Large?Pork,\nCase Eggs Show\ntrap.\nraid's ??#t->\nIn the United Slates cold storage\nstocks of food play an Important\npart In determining prices. For thai\nreason the monthly reports Issued\nby the Department of Agriculture\non the stock held In the United\nStates have a very Important bearing\nOB the market. The following\ntable gives a summary of the total\ncold storage holdings of meats an<!\ndairy products on the first of February\nthis year, compared wit!\nholdings a year ago and a montt\nago.\nMEAT* AND DAIRY PRODUCT*.\nPer cent la\nPer test U- ereaao or He\nereaM or do- Jas. 1, creaao ce?\ncrease com- 1?M. P??d to\npared to year laat\nago. Pooads. oatt.\nM +111 al.454.TW tt.\n87 25.7 51.1W.70S 20.1\n00 87.5 18.S75.455 8#\ntc 51.2 T7.i25.DW\nin 12.3 79.025.000 2.\n80 +#02.5 H8.081.W0 14.\n?50.5 142.812. W4\nx, 1?.0 5M.288.872 28.1\n,17 25.2 75.420.47? 12.1\nM -T 17.8 1.118.818.258 10.\nIn the middle Atlantic 8tates. whlcl\nincludes the port of New York.\nCold storage holdings of beel\nproducts amounted -to only 142.000.\n000 pounds this year compared wit*\n288,000.000 pounds a year ago am\nwith 326.0t0.000 pounds on Febru\nary 1, 1818. The latter figure represents\nalmost tha record holdings o!\nbeef In this country. Present holdl,.cs\nare approximately the aame ai\nsame as on January I of this year\nStorage holdings of pork products\nIncluding lard, total 7S6.000.00I\npounds which is about 1? per cen\nless than that on the correspondint\ndate in 1820. The record cold stor\nage holdings of pork products wen\nthose OB July 1. 1820, when the tota\namounted to 1,176.000,000 pound.\nFrozen pork was the only porl\nproduct which showed an Increase\nthis year compared with last. Thi\nholdings In this commodity amount\ned to 148.000,000 pounds compare!\nwith W7.000.000 pounds last year\nStocks of frosen poultry weri\nsmaller than usual. The total hold\nIngs were 81.000.000 pounds, or 11,\n000,000 pounds under last year i\nstock and 38,000.000 pounds less thai\nthe quantity held In 1819- Holding!\nof case eggs amounted to only 33.\n600 cases, or 1.8*3,000 pounds, whicl\nis the lowest amount ever recorde<\nin storage at this time of the year\nCroaen eggs on the other hand wen\nextremely large, showing an in\ncrease of Si per cent compared wlti\na year ago. Stocks of butter weri\n11 pet cent larger than last year\nwhile total cheese holdings showci\na decrease of nearly 26 per cent\nStocks of American cheese amounted\nto 25,000.000 pounds compared wltl\n43,400,000 pounds a year ago. Mos\nother varieties showed a slight in\ncrease over last year.\nSurvey Canadian\nMineral Land\nVANCOUVER. March 6.?The mot\nImportant mining development li\nBritish Columbia In the new yea\nwas contained in the announcemen\nby lh'i. William Sloan todsy tha\nthe Canadian Pacific wllL. immedl\nately begin through survey of 3.\n000.000 acres of mineral bearini\nlands which it owns on Vancouve\nIsland. The work will be carrie\nout under direction of the manage\nment of the Trail Smelter which I\nowned by the Canadian Pacifl\nRailroad.\nIn the view of the minister o\nmines this examination will bi\nforerunner of the establishment o\nsmelter by Canadian Pacific Rail\nroad on Vancouver island. Coppe\ni-nd coal discoveries are expected t\nbe developed through work to b\ndone this year. The survey will oc\ncupy a big staff through severa\nseasons. The Canadian Pacific Rail\nroad took over the lands years ag\n'from E. and N. Railways, owned b\nDunsmuirs. who originally got titl\nfrom Federal government by way o\nsubsidy for the building of th(\nrailway.\nhave a tendency to remove conges\ntion. besides giving the opportun\nity for the fresh trade.\n\"It Is necessary to look at thes\nmatters from a business point o\nview, and we should be prepare\nto show elasticity in dealing wit,\nthem in the same way as an indi\nvidual would do.\"\n3E NATIONAL\nOF NEW\nAND BRANG\n?ed Statement of Condition\nASSETS\nHand, in Federal Reserve Bank,\nBanks, Bankers and U. S. Treasure\ne* oi Other Banks\nttes Certificate* ol Indebtedness\nDiscounts\n?es Bonds, other Bonds and Se