, man\nt facturers and public officials wl\nare primarily interested in tl\ni building industry, wherein the fac\ne of the situation might be arrived\nwith the resultant efTect of redu\n1 tion of costs, which arc maintain^\n*t a high level through agreeme\na or lack of competition.\nt Fear of lavestera.\nCol. John Price Jackson, head\nthe industrial relations committ\nr of the Philadelphia Chamber\nCommerce, declared investors fear\nputting money in construction lc\nthey lose It through deflation\n8 values.\nDaniel Crawford, jr., president\nthe Philadelphia Operative Builde\n1 Association, estimated the shorta\nn of homes at l,500.0n0.\nr\nt Factory Production\nFails to Increai\nRIGA. February 15.?The Kn\nnaya Gaseta flnds that the Sov\na government is quite unable to i\ncrease the productivity of the P?\nersburg factories. Despite the fa\nc that during the first half of Ja\nuary some 6.000 workmen return\nto the factories from the villag\nthe productivity continues to f*\nthe quality and capability of t\nworkers are bad. and the quality\nr -the goods produced still worse.\no\nCoal Trade Needs\nSupport, Says And rat\no 1\ny NEW YORK. Feb. 6?The ban\ne ing interests of the country mi\nf stand behind the coal exporter\nthe United States is to retain\nforeign bituminous coal trade.\nr Andrade. jr., president of the who\nsale Coal Trade Association of N<\nYork, said here recently.\nWithout credits the United Stal\nwill fall under Great Britain In 1\ntuminous export trade, he said.\nd Wholesale prices of commoditi\nh says the Department of Labor, w<\nlower in November than any til\nsince the war.\nCITY BANK\nrORK\nHES\nas of February 21, 1921\ndue\nr $202,590,471.07\n5,571,008.88\n10,075,000.00 $21*336,479S3\n622,967,236.53\ntea 33,306344.56\n2350.000.00 658,824,081.09\n5,000,000.00\n$2,119316.13\ni 5,653349JO\nTOTAL $969,834,026.37\nBS\n$106,982375.99\n$82,692,131.08\n$31934931\n0 431530437\n3,007,764,44\n1,401367JO\nadd Jrith ir\" 143'64S'862*\nsoia witn ov\n33.447335.41\nelera' Checks $4,060,133.09\n2328300.00\n1333302.44\nTOTAL $969334,02637\nSpain's Lumber Need*\nTotal Enormous Amount\n8paln. under normal condition*\nrequires about board feet\nannually, to supply lt? need? for\n,1 lumber and foreat products, according\nto American \">rade Commlaaloner\nNelson C. Brown In a special reH\nport on the market Just published\nby the Bureau of Forel?n and Domestic\nCommerce of the Department\nof Commerce.\nLimited native production necessitates\nlarge imports. Of the tmport5\ned supply amounting to about Ml.000,000\nboard feet in ltll. the countries\nbordering on the Baltic furnl\n(shed about half. The United\nStates supplied about 76,000,000 feet,\nmost of which was Southern yellow\npine, and the remainder largely red\ngum and white oak.\nfflGHRATES HURT\nCANADA BUSINESS\nid\n?e increased Rail Charges Have\nCaused Grain Shippers to Send\nProduct Through U. S.\nn, i\nOTTAWA, Ont., March Railway\nc- rates and w&g?s constitute a bii?\n.11 problem in Canada as they do in\nBt the United State*, and both must\ncome down before n<ymal business\nrt conditions resume. Canada has built\nup a large railway system on na*e\ntlonal lines, but In respect to Tates\nand wagcx, American standards\ndominate the situation. An Increas.\nin wages in the United States is\n,n the signal for an Identical demarvi\net in Canada and the name is true\nB. of rates.\nThat the Canadian lines are losing\nmuch business through the pre8t\nvailing high rates is unquestionably\ntrue. The latest Increases in the\nle fall were of a temporary nature.\n|g a partial reduction having gone Into\nry' effect at the end of the year and\nothers will follow by July 1. As\nin an indication of how wages have\ngone up. on March 1. 1918, there\nne was an Increase of 15 per cent; on\nAugust 12. 1918. another of 25 per\n,j. cent, and in September, 1920, of 4n\nht Per cent.\nn_ The effect of these Increases on\nthe long haul, especially for grain,\nof has been to send a great deal of\nh it by the cheaper lake and rail route\nor to American ports, it having been\nfound that of 81.000.000 bushels of\nu. wheat exported between September\nno 1 and December 31. only 18,000.000\nhe went by Canadian ports,\nts Passenger Trifle Als* Hit.\nat Pas.senpcr traffic also has been hit\nc\" I by the high rates, especially for\np\" I sleeping and parlor cars.\nnll In six years the gross cost of operating\nCanadian railways has increased\nnearly $250,000,000. The Ca0f\ntmdlan Pacific is one of the largest\nee and best managed systems in th\nQf world, and because of Its excellent\nmanagement it has been enabled to\n,8t stand up well under the heavy strain\njn of increased .cost of operations\nDuring 1920 its earnings were $216.641.000.\nthe greatest by far in th?\nrs- history of the company, but though\nKC its earnings were more than double\nthose for 1910 the operating coal\nhad so increased that the net wa?\nwith the exception of that for 1919\nthe smallest of any year since 1910\nbeing $3,000,000 below the 1910 net\n9e when the revenue only stood a\n$100,851,629\nThe increased cost of operatioi\nhas fallen heaviest upon the Cana\ndian National, or government sys\ntem. which even under the best ol\n2 conditions could hardly be expected\nto make ends meet. In 1919 its op\nerating expenses increased fron\nc $84,000,000 to $108,000,000. chief!:\ndue to the advance in wages. Thi\nminister of railways is authority foi\nthe statement that out of ever:\ndollar of revenue earned by the Ca\nnadian National system In 1919, 71\ncents were paid out in wages. Th<\n1920 statement of the governmen\nroads will show an even worse stat<\nof affairs.\nNot only have *he high freigh\n,k- and passenger rates reduced traffic\nist but they are directly responsibl\nif for much of the discontent amonj\nIts the Western farmers, who. grlev\nC. ously disappointed at seeing th\nte- price of their chief crop, wheal\new greatly reduced, have also had t<\nendure further loss through hlghe\ntes fre