\npublic had less money to spend for\npointing. aggravated the situation,\nand resulted in a reduction of the\nactual wage payments.\nThat illustrates the whola situation.\nIt is short-sighted to be always\nthinking that wages are fixed\nby simply an agreement between\nemployer and employe, and\nthat the employer either can pay It\nout of his own pocket or pass it\non to the consumer. There Is a\nrelationship between each isdustry\nand all the other industries which\nmust be taken into the account.\nCANADIANlRADE\nREACTION SLOW\nLimited Price Inflation Fairly\nSteadies Business Per\nCapita.\nWINNIPEG. Kan.. March (.?Trade\nreaction seems to have hit a faster\npace in the United States and Canada.\naccording to statistics compiled\nby industrial experts who point out,\nhowever, that inflation was less in\nCanada, prices not having touched\nthe peak to which they were carried\nin the United States. As a consequence.\nbusiness per capita hai\nremained fairly steady.\nThese figures show that during\nmost of 1920. a year of falling business.\nCanada was doing more than\ntwice the foreign trade per capita\ncarried on by the United States\nThe comparii?ons are based on figures\nfor the first ten months period\nof 1920. The United States imported\n$4,692,283,000 worth of goods, compared\nwith $3,098,914,000 the previous\nyear. It exported $6,832,323.000\nworth, compared with $6,496.000.000.\nIn the same period of 192C\nCanada's exports were $992,374,664\nand imports $1,152,367,000 Allowing\n105.000.000 as the population ol\nthe United States and 8.500.000 for\nCanada, this works out per capita\nas follows\":\nr S. Canada\nKxports $65.00 $117.00\nImports 44.70 135.00\n$109.70 $252.00\nImports from the United Statef\nSUPPLYIN\nNE\nIT HAS BEEN the\nclianics Metals\nwhole of its exist\nten years to use its fu\nthe greatest possible I\nThe separate Ban\nInvestment Departmci\nview to meet the spe\nroutine requirements o\nAn opportunity to\ncorned.\n(MM.\nTheMecha\nXatio:\noftKc&t